  "number": "8.1",
  "title": "Latex - Typing Mathematics",
  "body": " Latex - Typing Mathematics   Getting Started in Overleaf    Create an account on https:\/\/www.overleaf.com    You can copy\/paste or upload the HW template document found on canvas    Save a copy of this for starting a homework assignment so that the original copy remains as a template in your files    Edit the existing template, copy\/paste or use the same text to add new sections, proofs, etc.    After you make changes, click \"recompile\" and the pdf will update and save    A cool thing about overleaf is that you can have different people sharing and working on a document together by sharing a document link      The Basics  Whenever you want to write math, or use symbols, you need to start and end with a dollar sign. So if you type:  Consider the equation   A single dollar sign on either end will keep your math in line with the text [shown below]:  Consider the equation   Display math mode will center your lines of math on their own line. To accomplish this, use 2 dollar signs on either end. So your code will look like:  Consider the equation   The output in latex will look like:  Consider the equation   Aligned equations will allow you to have multiple lines of equations where your equal signs are aligned:    Resulting output:     Note: the & symbol tells latex to align the next symbol with the previous & symbols. The two backslashes at the end of a line tell latex to end that line and start a new one.    Commonly Used Symbols and Codes      Troubleshooting  If your code won't compile:    If you are using overleaf, it will help you find errors in your code    Make sure commands use a backslash [\\] rather than a forward slash [\/]    You may be missing a dollar sign    Check your spelling on commands [ie. \\epslion rather than \\epsilon]    You may be missing a starting or ending bracket     If you have a \\begin command, you need an \\end command    remove spaces beween lines if you are in an itemize\/list\/align environment    If you don't know the code for a particular symbol\/object\/format:    If you don't know a symbol or how to format something - google it. \"how to write a matrix in latex\" etc.    You can copy\/paste others code    If code you find online wont run - look at their preamble information to see if they used a package you have not included    Ask for help if you can't figure something out!    Other Useful Stuff  For finding symbol codes:  Detexify can help if you don't know the code for a particular symbol https:\/\/detexify.kirelabls.org\/classify.html  For inserting images:   For coding matrices:      "
